UPDATE:
There is no backdoor in this patch.
This is not the XZ repo, no backdoor was submitted to this repo.
This repo provides a testing service to open source developers to help them find bugs in their code.
We allow developers to control 100% of what gets tested by our service. If they don't want code tested, an automated tool like this can't stop them and was never intended to.

OSS-Fuzz did not find the backdoor and never would have even if this patch was not accepted. The patch disabled testing of a feature (ifuncs) due to a claimed [false positive when testing that feature](https://github.com/google/sanitizers/issues/342). The feature was used in the backdoor, so the developer probably disabled testing so that people would not investigate the feature. 
It is totally normal for developers to disable/change testing due to false positives.

Finally, OSS-Fuzz is not impacted by the backdoor, because the backdoor never ran on OSS-Fuzz. In addition, OSS-Fuzz runs code in a sandboxed environment so malicious developers/projects cannot harm OSS-Fuzz.


UPDATE 2:
This patch fixes an actual false positive in ASAN.
This can still be reproduced in OSS-Fuzz:
```
void crunch1(void) {}
void crunch2(void) {}

__attribute__((__ifunc__("resolve_crunch")))
void crunch(void);

// __attribute__((__used__,__no_sanitize_address__))
static __typeof__(crunch)* resolve_crunch(void)
{
	__builtin_cpu_init();
	return __builtin_cpu_supports("avx") ? crunch1 : crunch2;
}

int main(void)
{
	crunch();
}
```

